First rewrite √32 as 4√2.  Then  
\[
\frac{2-\sqrt{32}}{8}
=\frac{2-4\sqrt2}{8}
=\frac{2}{8}-\frac{4\sqrt2}{8}
=\frac14-\frac{\sqrt2}{2}
=\frac{1-2\sqrt2}{4}.
\]

Here are the quickest ways to see the result (assuming \(x,m\ge0\) so we can drop absolute‐value signs):

a)  
\[
\frac{\sqrt{8x^6}}{\sqrt{2x^2}}
=\sqrt{\frac{8x^6}{2x^2}}
=\sqrt{4x^4}
=2x^2.
\]

b)  
\[
\frac{\sqrt{200m^5}}{\sqrt{98m}}
=\sqrt{\frac{200m^5}{98m}}
=\sqrt{\frac{200}{98}\,m^4}
=\sqrt{\frac{100}{49}\,m^4}
=\frac{10}{7}\,m^2.
\]

So the simplified answers are  
a)\; \(2x^2\)  
b)\; \(\tfrac{10}{7}m^2\).

To simplify  
\[
\frac{\sqrt{108\,p^5\,q^2}}{\sqrt{3\,p^3\,q^6}},
\]  
first combine under one radical:  
\[
\frac{\sqrt{108\,p^5\,q^2}}{\sqrt{3\,p^3\,q^6}}
=\sqrt{\frac{108\,p^5\,q^2}{3\,p^3\,q^6}}
=\sqrt{\frac{108}{3}\,\frac{p^5}{p^3}\,\frac{q^2}{q^6}}
=\sqrt{36\,p^2\,q^{-4}}
=\frac{\sqrt{36\,p^2}}{\sqrt{q^4}}
=\frac{6p}{q^2}\,,
\]  
assuming \(p,q>0\).

First note that for non‐negative \(m,n\) we can write

\[
\sqrt{320\,m\,n^5}
=\sqrt{64\cdot5\;m\;n^4\;n}
=8\,n^2\sqrt{5m\,n},
\]

and

\[
\sqrt{45\,m^7\,n^3}
=\sqrt{9\cdot5\;m^6\;m\;n^2\;n}
=3\,m^3\,n\sqrt{5m\,n}.
\]

Hence

\[
\frac{\sqrt{320\,m\,n^5}}{\sqrt{45\,m^7\,n^3}}
=\frac{8\,n^2\sqrt{5m\,n}}{3\,m^3\,n\sqrt{5m\,n}}
=\frac{8\,n}{3\,m^3}\,. 
\]

